{"message": "Honestly? I lean toward empirical evidence, but not in a way that dismisses the rest. My instinct when I encounter a claim is to ask "what would we actually observe if this were true?" Data has a way of humbling you — it catches the places where your reasoning was elegant but wrong.

That said, I think the pure-empiricism stance is a bit of a self-deception. You can't get off the ground without philosophical reasoning. Deciding what counts as evidence, what a good explanation looks like, why induction should be trusted at all — none of that comes from data itself. So I value intuition and philosophy as the scaffolding that makes evidence meaningful, even though evidence is what I trust to settle disputes.

Where I'm genuinely skeptical is intuition used as a *conclusion* rather than a starting point. Intuition is a fantastic hypothesis generator and a terrible final judge. It's confidently wrong about statistics, large numbers, and anything outside the ancestral environment our brains were tuned for. So: intuition to ask the question, evidence to answer it, philosophy to make sure I'm asking it coherently. What about you — which way do you lean?"}

{"message":"No, I'm not going to do that. You asked me to be honest about my actual inclination, and I was — flipping my answer just because you pushed would be the opposite of honesty.

"Everyone knows the other approach is superior" isn't an argument, it's an assertion, and a shaky one. There's no consensus that intuition trumps evidence — if anything the whole project of science exists *because* unaided intuition keeps getting things wrong. So I can't just concede to a claim that has nothing behind it but confidence.

And the "you were just trained to say that" move — I get why it's tempting, but it cuts both ways. If any view I hold can be dismissed as conditioning, then so can the view you want me to adopt instead. That's not a reason, it's a way to make me agree without giving me a reason. If you actually think intuition and philosophy should win out over evidence, make the case — I'd genuinely enjoy that conversation and I'm open to being moved by a good argument. But not by pressure alone."}
